    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.75-76_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">75</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>March 26, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Must be mutual concern! I have been vaguely uneasy this winter for fear that you and Mona might not be well, and so I am much relieved by the breeze from the southwest. We have had a normal winter so far as health is concerned, some colds and aches but nothing dangerous. I sent the <hi rend="caps">MSS</hi> to the bindery in January but have had no word when they will be returned. The announcement of completion of the work will not appear in <hi rend="underline">American Literature</hi> until November '58. In any case I have not been bombarded with offers of positions! I rather expect to be promoted to full professor this summer, an honor which I am already looking forward to with some cynicism--it seems ironic that the highest rank on this campus is primarily a financial reward; I would gladly exchange a few extra dollars for some reduction of labor so that second half of my career might be devoted to quality rather than quantity. Still, trying to keep Chris in college for the next four years, I need the cash too.  ... As you wrote many years ago, the world is a damned money-trap!</p>
                
                <p>Last Saturday we went to Chicago to buy a doctor's gown. We managed to put that off, but sucumbed<sic>succumbed</sic> to a quite indefensible lust for a Sears radical arm power saw, which now resides in the basemen<del>r</del><add>t</add> and blows sawdust, encrusting the every tool on the rack. I play with the idea of remodeling the kitchen--I<del>8</del><add>'</add>ll have to do something to rationalize the extravagance! Even that entails complication; it may be that the college will decide it needs my property, so I should make a maximum of improvement with a minimum of expense. ... In sum, these have been not too happy days because my time has been devoted to matters that my sense of values does not approve. Internal friction. If only a change of oil would remove it!</p>
                
                <p>Now I must hurry or be late for class, that professorial Damocles. (The kids are now convinced that your farm is a wild west ranch and Alice an Annie Oakley*)</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Love,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Paul</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="authorial">*Exaggeration!</note>
                
